t: To the chief Musician, A Psalm and Song of David.
Praise*p waiteth for thee, O God, in Zion: and unto thee shall the vow be performed.
O*p thou that hearest prayer, unto thee shall all flesh come.
Iniquities*p prevail against me: as for our transgressions, thou shalt purge them away.
Blessed*p is the man whom thou choosest, and causest to approach unto thee, that he may dwell in thy courts: we shall be satisfied with the goodness of thy house, even of thy holy temple.
By*p terrible things in righteousness wilt thou answer us, O God of our salvation; who art the confidence of all the ends of the earth, and of them that are afar off upon the sea:
Which*p by his strength setteth fast the mountains; being girded with power:
Which*p stilleth the noise of the seas, the noise of their waves, and the tumult of the people.
They*p also that dwell in the uttermost parts are afraid at thy tokens: thou makest the outgoings of the morning and evening to rejoice.
Thou*p visitest the earth, and waterest it: thou greatly enrichest it with the river of God, which is full of water: thou preparest them corn, when thou hast so provided for it.
Thou*p waterest the ridges thereof abundantly: thou settlest the furrows thereof: thou makest it soft with showers: thou blessest the springing thereof.
Thou*p crownest the year with thy goodness; and thy paths drop fatness.
They*p drop upon the pastures of the wilderness: and the little hills rejoice on every side.
The*p pastures are clothed with flocks; the valleys also are covered over with corn; they shout for joy, they also sing.
